The statement , which was co-authored by 40 Founding Members , said Hong Kong currently enjoyed the rights conferred by the Basic Law , including the right to maintain a free trade port and a separate customs territory , to enter into and implement bilateral and multilateral agreements with different countries and regions of the world in the name of &quot; Hong Kong , China &quot; in various fields , including the economy , finance , shipping , trade , communications , tourism , culture and sports .
These rights are not granted by any foreign government or legislature .
Over the years , Hong Kong has strictly adhered to international agreements , rules , laws and business ethics , conducted business with various countries and regions , and engaged in cooperation in a wide range of related areas .
The statement said the U.S. House and Senate Foreign Affairs Committee &apos;s move to pass the bill was unnecessary and was merely a response to a call by its Hong Kong agents to intervene in Hong Kong &apos;s internal affairs and gain political leverage for their agents in Hong Kong .
Members of the Founding Fathers expressed deep regret and strong opposition to the move .
The statement noted that Hong Kong is an important trading partner of the United States and the source of the largest trade surplus .
The rule of law , a fair and free business environment and a clean society make Hong Kong a good location for American businessmen to do business .
This bill , in addition to hurting Hong Kong and the interests of the US itself , would make the Sino-US relationship even worse .
Hong Kong will , as always , unswervingly implement the policy of &quot; one country , two systems &quot; , continue to enjoy its rights under the Basic Law and earnestly fulfill its obligations , the statement said .
Hong Kong will continue to make its due contribution to the international community and to international commerce in the past , present and future .
26 ( Xinhua ) -- Both houses of the French parliament will discuss immigration policy reforms next week , according to the European Times .
French President Emmanuel Macron recently said that France cannot &quot; accept everyone &quot; , but at the same time work to &quot; properly accommodate &quot; .
Reports suggest that Macron is trying to find a middle ground on immigration to soften the impact of the looming debate .
In a recent interview in New York , the US , on the sidelines of the general debate of the UN General Assembly , Macron said he wanted a genuine two-pronged approach to immigration policy , one that struck a balance between humanitarianism and efficiency .
&quot; If France wants to be able to accommodate ( migrants ) properly , it cannot accommodate everyone , &quot; Macron said .
Macron outlined four priorities of his migration policy : granting asylum to refugees in need of protection as soon as possible ; promoting the integration of migrants more efficiently ; receiving and protecting all migrants entering French territory ; and more efficiently resettling those who entered France illegally and were not suitable to stay .
Whether illegal immigrants should be protected by the state medical aid system has been the subject of much debate .
Mr Macron said he hoped to &quot; assess &quot; the system , but not remove it , but limit it .
Following Macron ’ s remarks , Le Pen , the leader of the far-right “ National Alliance , ” tweeted that Macron ’ s position was “ empty talk . ”
A member of the right wing Republicans , Senate President Ruschel also said that immigration policy should be discussed in a &quot; softened &quot; but &quot; realistic &quot; way , indirectly criticizing Macron .
Vallau , a leftist Socialist MP , argued that France should “ accept more and better ” on the issue of immigration , and criticized Macron for “ playing around ” with the issue .
A year after its enactment , a new version of the Asylum and Immigration Act has divided opinion in the ruling party but failed to placate right-wing opposition parties , the report said .
Macron will need to do something about immigration policy , which will again be the focus of far-right attacks in the next general election in 2022 , but he will also risk angering the ruling party ’ s insiders on the left .
The lower house of the French National Assembly is reportedly set to debate immigration policy from 30 September , while the Senate will debate it from 2 October .
