Beware of using plastic tea bags to make tea !
A recent Canadian study found that a bag of plastic tea could release billions , if not billions , of tiny plastic particles , significantly higher than a person &apos;s estimated annual intake of microplastics , but there is no evidence that ingesting small plastic particles poses a threat to humans .
Researchers at Canada &apos;s McGill University reportedly found that by immersing a plastic tea bag in a cup of almost boiling hot water ( 95 degrees Celsius ) , the tea bag releases about 11.6 billion plastic particles and 3.1 billion smaller nanoplastic particles into the cup .
This amount is significantly higher than a person &apos;s estimated annual intake of microplastics .
According to research published earlier in 2019 , the average person eats at least 50,000 plastic particles a year while inhaling the same amount of microplastics .
Writing in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology , the researchers tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in Montreal shops and cafes , opened them , washed them and dipped them in almost boiling water for five minutes , and analyzed them with electron microscopes and spectrometers .
According to the study , they found that a single tea bag released more than 11.6 billion plastic particles , &quot; several orders of magnitude higher than the plastic charge of other food items . &quot;
Most tea bags are made from natural fibres , but many tea bag brands still use plastic to seal their mouths , the report said .
Some branded tea bags , which the researchers tested , have switched from paper to plastic .
Plastic particles are tiny pieces of plastic that researchers define to be between 100 nm and 5 mm in size and produced mainly by the decomposition of plastic waste .
Researchers found traces of plastic particles in air , soil , rivers and the deepest trenches around the world , as well as in tap water , bottled water , seafood and beer .
Researchers first detected plastic particles in human feces samples from several countries in different regions of the world in October 2018 .
To test the potential toxicity of the plastic particles released from tea bags , the Canadian research team placed daphnids in contaminated water and found that microplastics affected the behaviour of these daphnids and caused them to develop deformities .
According to the World Health Organization ( WHO ) , there is no evidence to date that ingestion of plastic particles poses a threat to humans .
However , the WHO noted that more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread into the environment and what impact they have on humans .
The researchers speculate that the large amount of plastic particles released by the bags may be due to the fact that the bags are in contact with boiling water and may break down or exude toxic substances even when &quot; edible grade &quot; plastics are heated above 40 degrees Celsius .
Mr Guterres said the climate emergency was the biggest threat to the survival of small island states .
There , a natural disaster can erode the development gains of a generation .
This has been illustrated by the hurricanes that have struck Barbuda , Dominica and the Bahamas this year .
About a quarter of people in small island developing States live at altitudes of 5 metres or less .
Relocation could seriously affect their societies and way of life and even raise issues of sovereignty and national identity .
At a summit on climate action on Monday , small island states worked together to achieve carbon-neutral 100 % renewable energy by 2030 , and they are once again leading the world in the right direction .
&quot; The climate crisis is piling up new injustices on top of the old ones , &quot; Guterres said .
Although small island developing States contribute little to global warming , they pay the highest price .
Because of their middle-income status , many countries are also caught in an accelerating and unsustainable cycle of disasters and indebtedness .
The world must act , and now is the time to make big decisions and invest heavily in small island developing States , &quot; he said .
Today &apos;s high-level meeting adopted a political declaration calling for finding ways to help small island developing States manage disaster risks , invest in climate-resilient infrastructure and make the transition to renewable energy ; and urged international agencies to help small island developing States , especially highly indebted middle-income countries , access finance .
Small island developing States are at the forefront of protecting and conserving Earth ’ s lifeblood , the oceans .
The latest special report , released this week by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change , confirms that the oceans have suffered the dire consequences of the climate crisis .
By the middle of this century , many regions could experience extreme sea level rise every year that would have occurred only once in a century .
The report warns that without significant investment in adaptation , some island countries are likely to become uninhabitable .
Pollution , overfishing and acidification have taken a huge toll .
In the past 150 years , the world has lost half of all living corals , while plastic pollution has increased tenfold in the past 40 years .
The demand from industry , shipping , mining and tourism is leading to a reduction in resources , including the maintenance of fisheries in many island communities .
Small island States also face high costs of transport , energy and infrastructure .
They are heavily dependent on a number of external markets , which make them vulnerable to price fluctuations .
Some States are also making efforts to address the security implications of illicit trafficking in persons , arms and drugs .
&quot; By solving one problem in the most challenging circumstances , the problem can be solved anywhere , &quot; Guterres said .
The efforts of small island developing States to achieve the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development will provide us with tools , lessons learned and examples for the world to learn from . &quot;
He stressed that small island developing States were a special case for sustainable development .
They require the long-term attention and investment of the entire international community .
