Study : U.S. National Healthy Eating Index slightly up but still challenging - Zhongxin
A recent study showed a modest increase in the U.S. government &apos;s healthy eating index from 56 to 58 over the past 16 years .
But with a full score of 100 , it &apos;s hardly cause for celebration .
Americans still face &quot; significant challenges &quot; in their diets .
Dr. Fang Zhang , one of the study &apos;s co-authors and a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts , said Americans continue to eat a disproportionate amount of foods that can cause heart disease , diabetes and obesity , the most common diseases among Americans .
The study was published online April 24 in the Journal of the American Medical Association .
The study was based on findings from a U.S. government health survey of 44,000 adults conducted between 1999 and 2016 .
&quot; Despite considerable improvements , significant dietary challenges remain , &quot; the authors wrote .
The challenges are known to include getting Americans to cut down on snacks , hot dogs , fat cattle , butter and other foods that contain saturated fat .
The study found that people &apos;s dietary intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5 % to 12 % , exceeding the recommended intake limit of 10 % .
The biggest improvement in the national diet was a drop in sugar intake from 16 % to about 14 % , but it was still too high .
Officials say the intake of added sugar in the diet should be less than 10 % .
The researchers attributed the decrease in sugar consumption to a reduction in people &apos;s consumption of sugar-flavored soft drinks , but Zhang stressed that sugars are often added to even less-sweet foods , such as yoghurt and ketchup .
Adults in the United States have seen a small increase in their diets of fruits , nuts , oats and other whole grains .
However , 2016 data show that these foods still account for less than 5 % of the daily diet .
Although people consume slightly less salt , and the reduction in fruit juice has led to lower quality carbohydrates , Zhang said they still account for as much as 42 % of daily calories , many of which come from refined white bread and other refined grains .
The study was based on biennial personal health surveys that asked adults to recall what they had eaten in the past 24 hours .
These health surveys have asked this question twice every few days since 2003 .
The government &apos;s Dietary Guidelines for Americans recommend adopting a &quot; healthy eating pattern &quot; to reduce the risk of chronic disease .
The guidelines state that people should eat more nutrient-dense foods such as vegetables , fruits , whole grains , low-fat dairy products , as well as seafood , lean meats , poultry meat , eggs , seed-based foods that can provide protein .
The number of Americans with diabetes nearly doubled , to more than 7 % , during the study period , and obesity rates have increased over the years – today , about 70 % of American adults are overweight or obese .
In addition , heart disease remains the leading cause of death for U.S. nationals .
