Economic and trade frictions affect the U. S. economy &quot; report card &quot; .
The economy &apos;s &quot; report card &quot; for the second quarter of this year showed that gross domestic product growth slowed sharply from the previous quarter , driven by a sharp drop in private-sector investment and exports .
Analysts pointed to economic and trade frictions and the resulting uncertainty as the main reasons for the second quarter &apos;s decline in private sector investment and exports .
The final revision , released by the US Department of Commerce on 26 June , showed that US GDP grew at an annualized rate of 2 % in the second quarter , the same rate as the previous revision , but well below the 3.1 % rate for the first quarter .
Consumption growth was the main factor supporting the US economy in the second quarter , the data showed .
Personal consumption spending , which accounts for about 70 % of the US economy , grew by 4.6 % in the quarter , boosting growth by 3.03 percentage points .
In addition , government consumer spending and investment led the economy by 0.82 percentage point .
However , private sector investment slid 6.3 % in the second quarter from the previous quarter , dragging the economy up 1.16 percentage points in the current quarter , and exports fell 5.7 % from the previous quarter , dragging net exports down 0.68 percentage points .
Barry Knapp , managing partner at Ainslie Macroeconomic Consulting , said private sector investment had not only failed to keep up with last year &apos;s growth , but had fallen sharply as trade frictions and rising uncertainty hit business confidence .
Mr Knapp believes that US corporate capital spending is expected to remain on the downside next year amid policy uncertainty .
Analysts believe that while consumption growth has been a strong support for the US economy in the second quarter , there is growing evidence that economic and trade frictions and the resulting uncertainty have dented consumer confidence and adversely affected the US consumer outlook .
In a recent survey , 38 percent of consumers spontaneously mentioned the negative impact of tariffs on the U.S. economy , a year-and-a-half high , University of Michigan economics professor Richard Curtin said .
For the future of the U. S. economy , analysts generally believe that the U. S. economy will continue to slow .
But some experts say both the U. S. industrial sector and financial markets will improve if economic and trade frictions are eased .
Kathleen Birch , global economist at the Economist Intelligence Unit , expects the US economy to continue its gradual decline this year , with growth slowing to a slower pace than in the second quarter .
Mark Zandi , chief economist at Moody ’ s Analytics , predicts that the US economy will grow by 2.3 % this year , assuming economic and trade frictions do not escalate , and will slow further to 1.6 % next year .
Ellen Hatzen , investment manager at Putnam Investments , said the biggest corporate concern at the moment is economic and trade disputes and the uncertainty they bring .
&apos;Economic and trade frictions are still the number one issue and the main cause of this year &apos;s volatility in U.S. capital markets , &apos; said Matt Mellor , equity strategist at Miller-Tabak Asset Management .
